The problem is that the program doesn't keep track of the most recent match
matched id. It only prints them and leaves `lastMatch` as "none". To fix th
this, we need to change it so that whenever a match occurs, `lastMatch` get
gets updated with the new item id. We also need an extra condition for when
when no matches are found in the list.

Here is the corrected code:

```tundra
val items = [
  { id: 4, matched: true },
  { id: 5, matched: false },
  { id: 7, matched: true }
];

var lastMatch = "none";
for(item in items) {
  if (item.matched) {
    print(item.id);
    lastMatch = toString(item.id); // convert the number to string before a
assigning it to lastMatch
  }
}

if (lastMatch == "none") {
  print("No matches found");
} else {
  print(parseNumber(lastMatch)); // if there is a match, parse back the num
number from the string
}
```
This program now prints each matched id once and then either the last match
matched id or "No matches found" if no items were matched. The function `pa
`parseNumber()` is used to convert the stored string value of an item id ba
back into its numerical form for printing at the end, as per Tundra's requi
requirements.
